<subSubSection id="3F814A66436B0DCFB0612F65CA796A0C" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph id="062404ABA20C55674BB37C8A6A8F3F2D" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="40EC390E9F79A5A7C4F318A8022B4EB0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Shrubs to 2 m, resinous. Leaves sessile; blades oblanceolate to lanceolate, 10-18(-20) mm long, (2-)3-4 mm wide, apically acute, basally cuneate, glandular-pubescent, the margins ciliate. Capitula with cylindrical involucres (15-)18-20 mm high, 7-8(-14) mm wide; phyllaries 3-6-seriate, lanceolate, the inner 20-21 mm long, 2.4-3 mm wide, the outer smaller; ray florets (5-)7-8(-10), the corollas 20-21 mm long, the tube 11-11.5 mm long, the outer lip 9-9.5 mm long, 2-3 mm wide, tridentate, the inner lip bipartite, 6-7 mm long; disc florets (7-)10-11(-12), the corollas white, 13-14 mm long, the tube 10-11 mm long, the lobes 7-8 mm long; anthers 5-6 mm long. Achenes [ray] 4.5-5 mm long, 1.2-1.4 mm wide, glandular; pappus c. 13 mm long; [disc] 5-5.5 mm long, 1 mm wide, glandular; pappus c. 12.5 mm long.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="21BEA310B9203E4CEF4CCB4492EB283A" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9CA5EAA7E61D2BF479EF2974EBCFE366" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B5A4D96640CEBCFF7812ABEB2308A6F1" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
In 
<taxonomicName id="42932E1456AB48849CF94FA9EBB9769E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Plazia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BF3A2C6C9C8AB4CDF319BCEAD5406F33" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Plazia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DF398B31AE25D4018AC09DFB2D788941" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Plazia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="daphnoides">
<emphasis id="B695D9BE988D79A0A92C5E38B4EA8037" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Plazia daphnoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
displays the widest distribution with collections from the Andean Cordillera of southern Peru, Bolivia, Chile, and Argentina (3000-4000 m). While locally it may come while locally may come under stress from habitat reduction, it would be considered as of &quot;least concern&quot; (
<bibRefCitation id="AAE922650B40EE3BD657D62271AE149E" author="IUCN, Species Survival Commision" journalOrPublisher="Phytologia" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="B23" refString="IUCN, Species Survival Commision, 2001. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, United Kingdom, 1-30." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, United Kingdom, 1 - 30." year="2001">IUCN 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A7CA13BB17B04C52CF3086D971DB579A" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion.">
<paragraph id="B72E13F7E0DF6E2F367CFB072E2B0D15" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="799BEE795D8FE474CC9F71D5F0EF9953" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
This species is distinctive with the narrowest capitula with the fewest ray and disc florets within the genus. 
<bibRefCitation id="0A179B8306C83F80942EC85B386875DE" author="Ferreyra, R" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Sociedad Peruana de Botanica" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="B7" refString="Ferreyra, R, 1995. Family Asteraceae: Part VI, Tribe Mutiseae. In: MacbrideJF et al. Flora of Peru. Fieldiana Botany. N.S.35: 1-101." title="Family Asteraceae: Part VI, Tribe Mutiseae. In: MacbrideJF et al. Flora of Peru. Fieldiana Botany. N. S. 35: 1 - 101." year="1995">Ferreyra (1995)</bibRefCitation>
lists the type specimen as collected by H. Weddell near the locality of Tacora, which is now in northern Chile.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="03B7DB9F273C8DC04EAFEF2B437A923B" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<bibRefCitation id="788F74606897E7ABDB7E82907EEC7370" author="Weddell, HA" journalOrPublisher="Phytologia" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" publicationUrl="10.5962/bhl.title.217" refId="B24" refString="Weddell, HA, 1855. Chloris Andina, vol 1. P.Bertrand, Paris, 1-231. ., 10.5962/bhl.title.217" title="Chloris Andina, vol 1. P. Bertrand, Paris, 1 - 231." url="10.5962/bhl.title.217" year="1855">Weddell (1855)</bibRefCitation>
failed to describe a nominative variety (p. 13); however, the manner in which he presented the material examined in his studies suggests that his first variety represented his nominative variety [α 
<emphasis id="7586AA18D48338FC195B0FC56319618E" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">villosa</emphasis>
, foliis utrinque villosis]. Examination of a large suite of collections has failed to find consistant morphological variation combined with any geographic pattern to support recognition of varieties in this taxon.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EABBB93AB56D1005AB80EC75AC2BDFB4" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<normalizedToken id="A7F95D2C4D4F725731653A0068F741D2" originalValue="Robinson’s">Robinson's</normalizedToken>
(1980) new genus and species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C800C513E5876649FA0D30A4964E4CC" authorityName="H. Rob" authorityYear="1980" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Harthamnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="boliviensis">
<emphasis id="5469E18C8132BD3F8B430939394B005C" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Harthamnus boliviensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was discovered by him to be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="EA8F8BEB7EDEA726C9AB74C789DF2275" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Plazia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="daphnoides">
<emphasis id="4167361BA27581AEAC3B0AB13E5CDBFF" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Plazia daphnoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shortly after its publication.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
